Meine freundin guckt gerne diese Netflix Filme, die mein Algorithmus schön völlig vergessen hat. Also diese typischen „Schnulzen“ oder wie man immer die auch nennen will.

(BEISPIEL: Frau trennt sich nach turbulenter Beziehung (und geht häufig fremd) zieht von ihrem big city city big city job weg in die Pampa und übernimmt dort ein Bed and Breakfast von ihrer Tante, lernt brillanten Lyriker/Barkeeper kennen, der alten Leuten als Handwerker die Dächer kostenlos repariert, verliebt sich…und DANN kommt Raus, dass er eigentlich Millionär-Investor ist, der AUCH mysteriös aus der Stadt geflohen ist.

So oder in Variationen sind alle Stories.)

Dazu hört sie seit einigen Monaten Hörbücher, die bei uns durch multiroom im ganzen Haus laufen und ich somit immer wieder was mitkriege.

Eine Sache fiel mir auf: in den Stories mit einem „mysteriösen neuen Mann“ der irgendwo kennengelernt wird, kommt im Laufe der Story raus, das der Typ reich ist.

If you meant to use -られた as a honorific ending, keep in mind that this 尊敬語 (honorific speech used to talk about hierarchical superiors) and not 謙譲語 (honorific speech used to talk about oneself to hierarchical superiors). >>176638072
Actually in this context (passé composé), "finir" is used in its "participe passé" form, so you should accord it with the subject (because you're using "être" as your "auxiliaire").
The subject being singular ("c' " comes from "ça" or "ceci"), the "participe passé" is just "fini".

That's why you should write "c'est fini", and you could write "ils sont finis" or also "elles sont finies" in other situations where you would want to use "finir" in "passé composé".


If you want to learn about "passé composé" or french in general, you can use this website https://www.francaisfacile.com/exercices/exercice-francais-2/exercice-francais-50308.php#:~:text=Le%20pass%C3%A9%20compos%C3%A9%20est%20un,participe%20pass%C3%A9%20du%20verbe%20conjugu%C3%A9
It looks like shit but it still does the job most of the time

I think we all agree you should study grammar, it's just about in what manner and how much. Knowing the general gist of how a language works, like how it structures it sentences and how to recognize past/present/future are useful, it will help with comprehension and will help save you from scratching your head too much when inputting.

But I think the people memorizing 20+ verb forms and declension tables are going too far, especially since they know like 100 words and they're trying to write PERFECT sentences from the start. I think once you input enough, you're going to get the internal sense of what feels correct and what doesn't. And even if you don't, it's much easier to just fill in the gaps later once you can comprehend the language already and can much more easily notice the subtleties of grammar.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>176668591
Still not good enough to read books meant for natives. I'm at 2700 words in Anki at this point, but I think I've only internalized like half of that and some sentences can still trip me up and I have to do a double take to figure it out even when I know all the words. My listening is much worse and it takes like one unknown word to trip me up and I lose track of what's being said. I also made the mistake of reading without worrying about pronunciation so some words sound differently in my head than they actually should.

All in all, yes, reading helps with listening too. The comprehension you build with reading will trickle down into listening and then into what you can actually produce. Just make sure you're using audio while you're reading so you don't internalize words with the wrong pronunciation.

I'm currently making my way through German translation of Mistborn series so I get a taste of more native material. Still a lot of unknown vocab, but I'm using Language Reactor as a helper and can see instant translation and hover dictionary to fill in the gaps. It also has text-to-speech which is much easier to use than tracking down the audiobook and syncing it with the text.

Samarbejdspartneren havde allerede forladt Onkel Joakims bygning, da Onkel Joakim bemærkede, at sin fyldepen var væk.
Onkel Joakim ville hurtigt følge sin samarbejdspartner for at få fat i sin fyldepen igen, men før han tog afsted, havde hans sekretær prøvet til at spørge ham om noget vigtigt. Men Onkel Joakim svarede til hende, at hun bare skal fortælle det til ham senere, fordi han var nødt til at skynde sig.

Da Onkel Joakim endeligt fandt sin samarbejdspartner i byen og havde spurgt ham om fyldepennen, svarede han blot, at han hurtigt bemærkede, hvordan han tog en fyldepen af ham ved en fejltagelse, og at han bare havde givet den til Onkel Joakims sekretær, før han forlod Onkel Joakims bygning.
